The paper presents a new method for estimating posterior probabilities of structural features in Bayesian networks, which is a common problem in machine learning and artificial intelligence. Therefore, cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) are the most likely sub-categories. The method also involves Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) sampling, which is a common technique in computational statistics and data science, suggesting cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) as another likely sub-category. The paper also deals with partial orders on the nodes, which is a topic in combinatorics and discrete mathematics, suggesting cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) as a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper involves computing conditional probabilities, which is a topic in information theory and probability theory, suggesting cs.IT (Information Theory) as a possible sub-category.
